Read the CTD Data Log File¶

  1. Edit the CTD_Log_File_Path variable so it points to your CTD data log file.
In [24]:
CTD_Log_File_Path = '/Volumes/GoogleDrive/My Drive/SSROV Level 3/Open CTD Shared Files/Data Examples/Mid-Warf dunking w CTD 10:20:20/Log.csv'
# CTD_Log_File_Path = '/Volumes/GoogleDrive/My Drive/SSROV Level 3/Open CTD Shared Files/Data Examples/DATALOG Warf End Multiday 10:2:20.csv'

if not os.path.exists(CTD_Log_File_Path): # Check if the 'CTD_Log_File_Path' doesn't go to an acutual file. (If it does run this code)
    
    print("CTD Log File Path not Found!")

else:  

    # Use pandas.read_csv (The `read csv` function/tool from the Pandas library) to load the table from the file into the variable 'ctd_data'
    raw_ctd_data = pandas.read_csv(CTD_Log_File_Path,index_col=False, parse_dates=['Date Time'],infer_datetime_format=True,skipinitialspace=True)

# Now display the first 5 rows of data as a table using the 'head' function:

Convert CTD Sensor Values into Common Units in a new Pandas Table (called a 'Dataframe')...¶

  1. Pressure (Milibar) -> Depth (Meters)
  2. Condutivity -> Salinity (PSU)
  3. Find the Average Teperature from the three probes.
In [25]:
# Constants Used in the conversions. - Edit these if needed...
TemperatureOffset = 0 # Degrees C
PressureAtSeaLevel = 1010 # Milibar
SeawaterReferenceConductivity = 42900 # (35 psu, 15C)

# Average Temperature from the 3 Probes Calculation:
average_temp = (raw_ctd_data['Temp A'] + raw_ctd_data['Temp B'] + raw_ctd_data['Temp C']) / 3 + TemperatureOffset

# Pressure to Depth calculation:
depth = ((raw_ctd_data['Pressure'] - PressureAtSeaLevel) * 100) / 9810

# Conductivity to Salinity Calculation:
ratio = raw_ctd_data['Conductivity'] / SeawaterReferenceConductivity
rt = 0.6766097 + (0.0200564 * average_temp) + 0.0001104259 * (average_temp**2) -0.00000069698 * (average_temp**3) + 0.0000000010031 * (average_temp**4)
Rt = ratio / rt
ds = ((average_temp-15)/(1+0.0162*(average_temp-15)))*(0.0005+(-0.0056)*(Rt**0.5)+(-0.0066)*Rt+(-0.0375)*(Rt**1.5)+(0.0636)*(Rt**2)+(-0.0144)*(Rt**2.5))
salinity = 0.008+(-0.1692)*(Rt**0.5)+25.3851*Rt+14.0941*(Rt**1.5)+(-7.0261)*(Rt**2)+2.7081*(Rt**2)+ds

# Create a new pandas table (known as a dataframe):
ctd_data = pandas.DataFrame(columns=('Date Time','Depth','Salinity','Average Temp','Temp A','Temp B','Temp C'))

# Fill the new table with the values we calculated. 
# Here ctd_data['Date Time'] means get the 'Date Time' column of the ctd_data table. 
# "=" means set the colum on the left of the equals sign to be the same as the column on the right:
ctd_data['Date Time'] = raw_ctd_data['Date Time']
ctd_data['Depth'] = depth
ctd_data['Salinity'] = salinity
ctd_data['Average Temp'] = average_temp
ctd_data['Temp A'] = raw_ctd_data['Temp A'] + TemperatureOffset
ctd_data['Temp B'] = raw_ctd_data['Temp B'] + TemperatureOffset
ctd_data['Temp C'] = raw_ctd_data['Temp C'] + TemperatureOffset

# Now display the first 5 rows of the new table using the 'head' function:
ctd_data.head(5)

Plot CTD Results Over Time...¶

After running this code, use the tools on the right to explore the chart ...

  • To zoom in, Click the Scroll Zoom tool: & scroll with two fingers on your trackpad
  • To scale individual axies: Click the Scroll Zoom tool: & move your mouse over an axis, then scroll with two fingers on your trackpad.
In [27]:
# use the hvplot libraries' line funtion on the ctd_data table to make a line chart.
# The '('  here is actually the start of the parameters you give to the 'line' function.
#  - Note how each line (or parameter) ends with a comma! 
ctd_data.hvplot.line(
    x='Date Time', # < Use the 'Date Time' colum on the x-axis
    y=['Depth','Salinity','Average Temp'], # < Plot each of these columns on the y-axis.
    height=500, # < Make the plot this many pixels tall.
    responsive=True, # < Make the plot as wide as will fit on the screen.
    datashade=False, # < False here means don't use datashader which is only useful for really large amounts of data.
)

Plot Temp & Salinity Over Depth...¶

Use a filtered dataset to limit the depth range of the displayed data. For more filter examples see: https://www.ritchieng.com/pandas-multi-criteria-filtering/

In [30]:
# Make a filtered_data table with only the rows from the ctd_data table where the
# # depth was greater than 0.1m and the depth was less than 30m 
filtered_data = ctd_data[
    (ctd_data['Depth'] >= 0.3) & (ctd_data['Depth'] < 30)
]

# # example filter for data in the time between 10:40am and 2pm (13:00) on september 12: (to use it: uncomment & edit the next 3 lines)
# filtered_data = filtered_data[
#     (ctd_data['Date Time'] > datetime.fromisoformat('2020-10-12 10:40')) & (ctd_data['Date Time'] < datetime.fromisoformat('2020-10-12 14:00'))
# ]

# make a scatter plot from the filtered_data with depth on the x axis and avg temp & salinity on the y:
depthx = filtered_data.hvplot.scatter(
    x='Depth', # < Use the 'Depth' colum on the x-axis
    y=['Salinity'], # < Plot these columns on the y-axis.
    c = 'Average Temp', # < color the points based on this axis
    clabel = 'Avg Temp *c', # < Add a label to the color scale
    cmap = 'viridis', # <- The name of a 'color map' or color gradient to use. For more color maps, see: http://holoviews.org/user_guide/Colormaps.html
    height = 500, # < Make the plot this many pixels tall.
    responsive = True, # < Make the plot as wide as will fit on the screen.
#   datashade = True, # Uncomment this line to use datashader which is only useful for really large amounts of data.
#   dynspread = True # If you turn on datashader above, uncoment this line to make individual points more visible.
)

Add a time range selection at the bottom of the chart..¶

Drag to on the bottom plot to highlight points that fall within that time range

In [32]:
import holoviews as hv
from holoviews.plotting.links import DataLink
from holoviews import opts
hv.extension('bokeh')

timeRangePlot = filtered_data.hvplot.scatter(
    x='Date Time',
    y='Date Time',
    c='Average Temperature',
    hover=False,
    tools=['xbox_select'], # <-
    flip_yaxis=True,
    height=80, 
    responsive=True, 
).opts(default_tools=[],active_tools=['xbox_select'],color='white')

DataLink(timeRangePlot, depthx)

layout = (depthx + timeRangePlot ).cols(1)
layout.opts(opts.Layout(shared_axes=False, merge_tools=False))

Plot each type of mesurement or table column as a seperate chart¶

Sometimes lines may look flat because the scale is off. To fix this:

  • Click the Scroll Zoom tool at the very top: & move your mouse over the y axis, then scroll with two fingers on your trackpad.
In [76]:
columns_to_show = ['Depth','Light Level','Salinity',['Average Temp','Temp A','Temp B','Temp C'],['Accel x','Accel y','Accel z'],['Pitch Angle','Roll Angle','Yaw Angle']]
output_plots = None
for column_name in columns_to_show:
    plot = merged_data.hvplot.line(
        x = 'Date Time', 
        y = column_name, #
        ylabel = column_name if (type(column_name) == type('Hi')) else column_name[0],
        responsive=True, 
        height=200, 
    )
    if output_plots is None: 
        output_plots = plot
    else:
        output_plots = output_plots + plot
output_plots.cols(1)
